<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,1684,2032]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis box="[199,636,1829,1853]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
Distribution (
<figureCitation box="[354,451,1829,1853]" captionStart="FIGURE 191" captionStartId="47.[151,250,1292,1315]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,193,1271]" captionTargetId="figure@47.[151,1436,193,1271]" captionTargetPageId="47" captionText="FIGURE 191. Distribution of I. hospodar, I. rectipennis, I. pavelii, and I. thracica on the Balkan Peninsula." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/246568/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
Fig. 
<number box="[408,451,1829,1853]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="191.0">191</number>
</figureCitation>
) and phenology
</emphasis>
: The main range of the species covers the middle mountain ranges of the Pontic region of Northwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[541,638,1864,1888]" name="Turkey" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Anatolia</collectingCountry>
(up to 
<quantity box="[719,808,1864,1888]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="m" value="1800.0">1800 m</quantity>
). The species was described from the region of Istanbul and is possibly distributed along the Black-Sea coast of European 
<collectingCountry box="[898,978,1900,1924]" name="Turkey" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Turkey</collectingCountry>
and Istranca Mts, though until present it was only found in two localities in 
<collectingCountry box="[555,651,1936,1960]" name="Bulgaria" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Bulgaria</collectingCountry>
(Strandzha Mts) at 
<quantity box="[880,1008,1936,1960]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.25" metricValueMax="3.5" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="m" value="325.0" valueMax="350.0" valueMin="300.0">300–350 m</quantity>
alt., where it inhabits mesoxerophyte semi-ruderalized meadows and scrub surrounded by oak forests. Nymphs—III–V(–VI), imago—V–VII(–VIII in mountains).
</paragraph>
